Sure! You can use the `chessboard` package in LaTeX to draw a chessboard and the `chessfss` package to process FEN notation. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do it:

1. Make sure you have the `chessboard` and `chessfss` packages installed. You can download them from CTAN (Comprehensive TeX Archive Network) if they're not already included in your LaTeX distribution.

2. Start your LaTeX document with the `\documentclass` command and load the `chessfss` and `chessboard` packages. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessfss}
\usepackage{chessboard}
```

3. Inside your document, you can use the `fenboard` command from the `chessboard` package to draw the chessboard based on a FEN notation. For example, if you have a FEN notation like `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR` (which represents the starting position of a chess game), you can include it in your document like this:

```latex
\begin{document}

\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}

\end{document}
```

4. Compile your LaTeX document with a suitable engine, such as `pdflatex`, to generate the PDF output.

Here's the complete LaTeX code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessfss}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}

\end{document}
```

This code will generate a PDF with a chessboard drawn in the starting position of a chess game. You can replace the FEN notation with any other valid FEN string to draw the corresponding chessboard.

